nous peoples of the New World, bringing into focus the intersection of colonial expansion with the Inquisition and adding significant nuance to the entire question of the colonial encounter. Revealing the crucial tension between the Jews as “others within” and the Indians as “others without,” The Unconverted Self is a major reassessment of early modern European identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslam. 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aIndians of North AmericaxReligion. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aotherness, othering, new world, judaism, difference, anti-semitism, belonging, majority, identity, religion, christianity, islam, rhetoric, colonialism, indigenous, inquisition, expansion, colonial encounter, nonfiction, authority, community, aztec, anthropology, carnality, bestial, conversion, christendom, citizenship, dominance, crusades, history, displacement, incorporation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226069142423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226069142/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles